<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For some reason Channel 4 is staying very quiet about one aspect of its new
series Quarrels. The billing says these programmes 'bring together disputing
parties, whether individuals or groups', but in the first two episodes, at
any rate, race is a factor. Today a Muslim resident of Leicester confronts a
prostitute who works on the street outside his house (8.00pm). BBC2's series
on technology, White Heat, which began well last week, moves on to the
question of technological change: does it occur to supply a need, or do
innovations create their own demand? Until somebody created a disposable
nappy, nobody needed one. Fiction writers 'invented' death rays, and then
along came the laser which can shoot down aircraft, restore sight and read
bar codes - yet it was not invented to do any of those (8.00pm). BBC2
considers OJ Mania: The Media Trial Of OJ Simpson (11.15pm). Millions of
Americans watched the scenes live on television when Simpson set off up the
highway and was pursued by a phalanx of police cars. Some now doubt whether
Simpson can ever get a fair trial.
</TEXT>
