<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / Sport: King Lear at the Palace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Watching live athletics is almost as different as can be imagined from
watching the sport on television. At the World Cup meeting staged last
weekend at Crystal Palace, I spent several hours trying to think what,
exactly, the spectacle in the arena reminded me of. Eventually it clicked.
Anyone who has, during the last year or so, attended a performance by the
Royal Shakespeare Company will be familiar with those dumb show opening
scenes that directors so love. Convinced that they can improve upon the
beginning of, say, King Lear, they have their cast come on to the stage and
parade meaningfully, performing bits of silent business as they swerve
dramatically in their big boots. To the audience, the whole thing looks
pointless, indeed shambolic, though at the same time it is obvious that some
choreographic hand, some guiding principle, is behind it all.
The World Cup meeting looked just like that. On to the stage strolled
phalanxes of attendant lords and ladies, self-important in their badges of
officialdom. Then, in their midst, appeared a troupe of taut young men
wearing costumes that proclaimed their different factions; after a few
moments they began to perform complicated rituals, readying themselves for
acts of great dynamism. Suddenly, behind them, a small army of women began
to hurl missiles across the stage. The scene had filled with a diversity of
displays which pulled one eye in one direction and the other in at least
another three.
Television invests athletics with intense concentration but, in reality,
this is diffused by confusion: little ladies in blazers scuttle past Linford
Christie as he runs his lap of honour; discuses are thrown at Sally
Gunnell's head; medal ceremonies take place as, behind them, a lone 10,000
metres runner completes her race five minutes after the thing has been won.
Of course there are moments when significance is palpable within this scene,
as for example at the appearance of King Lear - Christie, himself. But these
are fleeting compared with the general impression of amiable chaos. What I
remember most is watching preparation rather than action. Most athletes
spend about 5 per cent of their time on stage doing what they are supposed
to be doing; 95 per cent of it they spend in revving themselves up, hobbling
up and down the track as if afflicted with gout, visualising, improvising
and, above all, getting dressed and undressed. In fact, what the World Cup
meeting really reminded me of was a rehearsal of an RSC dumb-show opening
scene.
But if the spectacle has the self-obsessed, faintly comical and occasionally
thrilling aspect of highbrow theatre, its audience is a very different one
from those who worship at the Barbican Centre. This crowd was, in fact, pure
David Cassidy concert audience circa 1973. All sporting crowds disseminate
different atmospheres, from the testosterone-suffused one at football
matches, to the Airwick-fresh one of tennis tournaments; here, the dominant
force is that of the teeny-bopper.
Adults become afflicted with it too, scurrying around Crystal Palace for a
glimpse of Du'ane Ladejo's back. Autograph books are carried like begging
bowls. Girlish wails fill the sky as Linford Christie removes his sweatshirt
though, since the screaming is just as loud for Gunnell, it is presumably
familiarity rather than physicality that causes the excitement.
It is a friendly atmosphere, pleasantly remote from the glamorised, moneyed
and almost decadent image of athletics that tends to be presented by the
media. There is something reassuring in the teeny-boppers' unquestioning
love for their heroes. This is partly because they are expressing something
that one might feel oneself, but would never dare to express so
uninhibitedly; partly too because they are cutting through the crust of
cynicism that has grown over the sport, and proving, with their trust, that
much of athletics is still trustworthy.
It may be that the atmosphere is rather different at, for example, those
Grand Prix meetings in which athletes compete for the proceeds of the
Brinks-Mat robbery. After all, the World Cup has at its heart a premise that
derives from the amateur tradition: it is an event in which competitors
represent nations or continents, rather than themselves, and at which
winners walk away with honour rather than with an armful of gold bars.
For this reason the World Cup is derided by some, who see it as almost
hypocritically inappropriate to the world of modern athletics.
Paradoxically, they also criticise any top athlete who fails to appear at
it.
Like the sport itself, such people seem uneasy with the current balance
between professionalism and amateurism - what, they wonder, ought to be
going on? Is it ridiculous, or is it charming, to expect supreme soloists to
want to subsume their identities into that of a nation or continent? The
fact is that it doesn't matter. The crowd at Crystal Palace proved that, as
it took constant pleasure in the notion of belonging to and owning a team,
but found real joy in the sight of individual greatness.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
