<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / Chipper outlook for spud supremos
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The humble spud is making a comeback against the combined onslaught of rice
and pasta, a conference in Harrogate, North Yorkshire, will be told today.
Delegates to the World Potato Congress, which opened last night with a gala
reception and a parade of flags of the 50 countries attending the two-day
event, will be told how advertising and ideas for new recipes have reversed
a drift away from the potato.
Consumption in the UK fell from 105kg per head a year in the early 1980s to
99kg in 1991 as consumers were attracted to 'glamorous' pasta or rice
dishes.
But an advertising campaign by the Potato Marketing Board, in its third year
of five, has helped push consumption up to 107kg, said Mr Bob Griffiths, the
board's marketing services manager.
The increase has been in processed potatoes but Mr Griffiths added: 'Our
efforts have stopped the slide in consumption of fresh potatoes.'
The campaign has focused on the nutritional value of potatoes and their
versatility. Consumer surveys suggest potatoes are difficult to prepare
compared with pasta, sales of which are rising 10 per cent a year.
So far the potato board has spent Pounds 5.5m on the campaign although the
industry might be seen as overreacting. Rice consumption, although 70 per
cent higher than a decade ago, is just 3kg per head in dry weight and pasta
consumption is just over 2kg. The retail potato market is worth Pounds 3.5bn
compared with an estimated Pounds 185m for pasta.
Potato prices have risen 50 per cent this year however, due to lower
plantings and a poor harvest. But Mr Griffiths insisted there is no evidence
of consumer resistance. 'People are prepared to pay more providing they get
a good-quality product.'
</TEXT>
