<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / Dairy trade launches court battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The dairy trade will this week begin its legal battle to overturn new milk
marketing arrangements which it believes will force up retail prices and
bring in a flood of imports.
The Dairy Trade Federation, which represents milk processors, intends today
to submit to the High Court its case for judicial review of the government's
approval of the scheme.
The hearing to decide whether it has an arguable case is expected later this
week or early next week.
Dairy companies are challenging the selling system introduced by Milk
Marque, the farmers' voluntary co-operative, which takes over when the
statutory Milk Marketing Board is abolished on November 1.
They say the auction system, under which they have tendered for supplies
from Milk Marque, has increased their costs by up to 24 per cent for some
dairy products.
Mr John Price, director-general of the federation, said its lawyers would
argue that Mrs Gillian Shephard, then agriculture minister, was wrong on two
counts under the 1993 Agriculture Act when she approved arrangements for
opening up the Pounds 3.3bn market in England and Wales in June.
'No reasonable minister knowing what she and her officials knew at the time
could possibly say this purchasing system took account of the interests of
purchasers,' he said.
Even if she believed that, Mrs Shephard was wrong to assume the scheme took
account of consumers' and farmers' interests and would lead to competition
in milk marketing, he said.
The dairy trade argues that Milk Marque, which controls 65 per cent of
supplies, has a monopoly of the market. Because of European Union milk
quotas, British farmers can produce only 85 per cent of domestic dairy
needs, and processors say they have little choice but to buy the bulk of
their milk from Milk Marque at the prices it sets.
Last week Tesco, the supermarket group, said UK price rises would force it
to buy dairy products from continental Europe.
If the federation wins leave for a judicial review, it hopes its case will
be judged next month before November's planned market deregulation.
</TEXT>
