<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / Rise of 4.5% seen for prices of homes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
House prices should increase an average of 4.5 per cent both this year and
next, according to Mr Patrick Moon, an economic adviser to Lloyds Bank.
Writing in the bank's economic bulletin, Mr Moon forecasts accelerating
price rises in later years, lifting prices an average of 5.5 per cent a year
up to 1998. However, only in 1997 will negative equity cease to be a drag on
the market.
Mr Moon's forecasts for this year and next year suggest that house prices
will rise somewhat faster than inflation.
However, this contrasts with reports last week from Halifax and Nationwide
building societies. Halifax, the largest lender, said prices had been
broadly stable since the beginning of the year while Nationwide said price
rises were likely to be close to the rate of inflation by the end of this
year.
Prices are forecast to rise fastest in the south-east over the next five
years with an annual average rate of 6.9 per cent while prices will rise
most slowly in the Yorkshire areas and Humberside, where the average annual
increase is expected to be 3.7 per cent.
</TEXT>
