<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / CBI armed for white paper war: Howard Davies' early and
unusual intervention in a departmental spending row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A row between the Treasury and the Department of Trade and Industry over
spending and taxation is not something that the Confederation of British
Industry would normally be involved in.
Although Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, has a habit of not
intervening unless he is sure of winning, he has made it clear that he will
continue to act as an irritant in Whitehall and Westminster if he senses any
Treasury backsliding over the white paper on competitiveness  - first
announced by the DTI.
Mr Davies is not about to sign up for everything the DTI does. Indeed, he
took the unusual step of publicly reminding Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and
industry secretary, that the white paper, published in May, had demonstrated
the need for business advice and support services as good as those available
in competitor countries.
This meant upgrading the services for small businesses at home and export
activity abroad. Yet these are the kind of schemes that the Treasury wants
scrapped. 'The whole point in having a competitiveness white paper was that
it set out government policy on spending and taxation across all
departments,' Mr Davies said.
Yet, as he told Mr Heseltine at a CBI dinner last week, the ink was scarcely
dry on the white paper before the Treasury began to throw the basis of the
policy into question.
Mr Davies was referring to the plans of Mr Michael Portillo, the former
Treasury chief secretary, to slash the DTI budget. These plans, when leaked
during the summer, caused a political row between the government's two
principal heavyweights - Mr Portillo and Mr Heseltine.
Mr Davies is concerned that the Treasury may feel that economic growth would
enable an abandonment of the principles of the white paper.
The CBI believes Britain must use the recovery phase to work on correcting
four deficits: the public sector borrowing requirement, the balance of
payments, the skills deficit, and the investment deficit.
The first is portrayed as a government responsibility. Mr Davies believes
the other three can only be solved by a partnership between the public and
private sectors.
'The DTI and the CBI have shown that they are ready to develop that
partnership. I hope that the rest of the government allow us to get on with
it,' he said.
Treasury officials have expressed surprise at the tone and content of Mr
Davies' remarks. Irrespective of the help they believe the government
already gives British industry, they remain adamant that the white paper
does not prevent them from questioning spending.
The Treasury's response may have been predictable, if not the one hoped for
by the CBI, but Mr Davies has taken heart from comments by Mr Heseltine that
the white paper represented the policy of the whole government.
'This (assurance) is what we wanted to hear,' Mr Davies said, an assertion
that the Treasury did not dispute. But although the CBI was on the winning
side in the latest departmental battle it will not be clear who has won the
war until after the latest spending round.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
