<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / Housing groups may be given credit ratings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The largest and strongest housing associations rank with larger property
investment companies and middle-ranking building societies as investment
opportunities, says a report published today by a credit-rating
organisation.
IBCA says that credit rating would give the larger, soundly financed
associations ratings in the single-A range. Such ratings would make it
easier for them to raise private finance to top up government grants for
building low-cost housing.
However, it warns that the attractiveness of associations to investors could
be reduced by further cuts in government grants or by significant reductions
in housing benefit.
Mr Jonathan Aitken, chief secretary to the Treasury, warned last week that
he would target housing benefit in the autumn public-expenditure round after
steep rises in the bill over recent years.
Housing benefit helps low-income households pay their rent, and is seen by
investors as underpinning associations' income streams. Attempting to reduce
the benefit at the same time as cutting grants is likely to produce severe
strains in the sector, it says.
The Housing Corporation, the quango that distributes government grant to
associations, estimates that associations will need to raise Pounds 7bn on
the capital markets over the next three years.
Those which achieved investment-grade ratings would be able to draw on a
much wider investor base and cut the cost of borrowing.
IBCA says that it would be prepared to rate associations and also the
debenture issues undertaken by groups of associations.
While the sector is closely regulated by the Housing Corporation, this would
not protect creditors in all circumstances, according to IBCA. There is also
a danger that greater competition for government grants - or fears that
grants may be harder to get in the future - will lead associations into
uneconomic development.
IBCA Credit Review of UK Housing Associations. IBCA, 2 Eldon Street, London
EC2M 7LS. Pounds 100.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
