FT  12 SEP 94 / Change in regional prosperity predicted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The economy will form a patchwork of boom-and-bust areas over the rest of
this decade, making obsolete ideas such as the north-south divide, a leading
forecasting company reports today.
The Henley Centre identifies the 50 areas with the best and worst prospects
and says the pattern of prosperity will become more polarised at a local
level as divides emerge within regions.
Within greater London, for example, the centre forecasts that areas such as
Kensington and Chelsea and the neighbouring borough of Hammersmith and
Fulham in will prosper, reflecting large numbers of professionals working in
growing information industries and expanding small-business sectors. Waltham
Forest, however, is among the bottom 25 because of a large overhang of
negative equity in the local housing market and a greater reliance on more
traditional industries.
The three main southern areas - the south-east, south-west and East Anglia -
account for 11 of the 25 winner areas and eight of the 25 worst areas.
In the north-west, Liverpool is in the bottom 25 while nearby Warrington is
in the top 25. The bright forecast for West Lothian in Scotland contrasts
with a poor outlook for Cumnock and Doon valley.
The factors it has considered include:
Underlying dynamism as illustrated by past performance in creating
employment.
Labour supply and whether there is an expanding, younger workforce with
up-to-date skills.
The entrepreneurial skills base and strength of local business.
The employment structure as reflected in the balance of growing and
declining sectors in an area and the distribution of head offices of big
companies.
Communications. Many of the coastal areas in the bottom 25 are peripheral to
national and international markets.
London has been voted the best European city in which to locate a business,
Healey and Baker, an international property consultancy, said.
Its fifth annual European Real Estate Monitor left the rankings of the top
six cities unchanged from last year. The next five in order were Paris,
Frankfurt, Brussels, Amsterdam and Zurich.
The rankings are based on a survey of 510 executives in nine European
countries.
Local Futures 94. The Henley Centre, 9 Bridewell Place, London EC4V 6AY.
Pounds 1,950 (half-price to the public sector).
