<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / Treasury to help axed staff on jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury is setting up an outplacement counselling scheme to find new
employment for staff made redundant in an impending shake-up.
The results of a fundamental review into the Treasury's operations are
expected to be delivered to Sir Terence Burns, permanent secretary, at the
end of this month. It is expected to recommend staff cuts and a reduction in
the Treasury's layers of management to reflect its changing role.
The review, being handled by Mr Jeremy Heywood, a former principal private
secretary to chancellors Mr Kenneth Clarke and Mr Norman Lamont, and
supervised by Sir Colin Southgate, chairman of Thorn EMI, was announced in
the Budget last November. Yesterday Treasury officials described as
'premature' a report that a third of its top 120 staff faced the axe.
Mr Heywood has been investigating the organisation of staff and the
allocation of resources inside the department. One particular challenge is
to adapt the Treasury, which oversees the government's economic and
budgetary policy, to decentralisation and delegation among the spending
ministries.
One of the aims is to place more emphasis in the Treasury on setting the
agenda and getting the framework for policy right. But if this is achieved
the department will be less involved in detailed supervision and
second-guessing of other ministries, with the result that some officials
will be surplus to requirements.
</TEXT>
