<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 94 / Poll blow for Japanese coalition: By-election defeat raises
prospect of creation of New New party
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's ruling coalition of socialists and conservatives was humiliated in a
by-election yesterday, the first measure of its popularity since it seized
power in a parliamentary coup 10 weeks ago.
The defeat in Aichi, the heartland of the car industry, gives a symbolic
boost to attempts by the 10 parties in opposition to merge into a single
party, able to rival the Liberal Democratic party for parliamentary clout.
Voters had condemned the coalition of the LDP with its long-time enemy, the
Social Democratic party, as 'an act of betrayal' and now wanted a
progressive new party, maintained Mr Tsutomu Hata, the former prime
minister. The LDP joined hands with the SDP to muster enough votes to oust
Mr Hata's five-party coalition government in June, so ending the LDP's first
spell in opposition for 38 years.
The outcome of yesterday's poll poses no immediate threat to the government,
since the Aichi seat - in the upper house, the less powerful of the two
parliamentary chambers - was already in opposition hands. It does not affect
the political situation, said Socialist prime minister Tomiichi Murayama.
But if yesterday's result does convince doubters among the opposition to
join forces with Mr Hata and his allies, this will, to the relief of many,
simplify Japan's convoluted politics. The new grouping has been
provisionally named Shin-Shinto (New New party) by the Japanese press.
The vote increases the stature of former prime minister Toshiki Kaifu, who
led the opposition campaign in Aichi, his home prefecture, and is widely
seen as a candidate to lead the new party.
The government nominee, a former United Nations official, Mr Jiro Mizuno,
was beaten by nearly 384,000 votes by the opposition candidate, a former
Labour Ministry bureaucrat, Mr Yuzuru Tsuzuki, who attracted just over
925,000 votes. Mr Mizuno modestly claimed the result was his personal fault
and did not represent a judgment against the government.
A low turnout in Aichi yesterday testified to apathy among the voters, jaded
by three changes of government in the past year. Only 43 per cent of the
electorate voted, below the 47 per cent of the previous upper house election
two years ago, but slightly ahead of the gloomiest newspaper predictions.
The seat became vacant after the incumbent was convicted of lying about his
academic qualifications in electoral publicity.
The third-placed candidate, a television talk-show hostess, Ms Makiko
Suehiro, played to voters' discontent by saying that her adversaries were
merely indistinguishable pawns in a Tokyo power game. Mr Hata is reported to
have provided evidence of that theory by mixing up candidates' names and
mistakenly urging his supporters to vote for the government nominee.
The government did no better. Ms Makiko Tanaka, director general of the
science and technology agency, called the government's candidate Mr Shimizu
instead of Mr Mizuno, at a rally.
Despite the elements of tragi-comedy at Aichi, the election was significant
in that it took place under conditions similar to those provided by reformed
electoral system for the more powerful lower house, due to come into effect
next year. This will introduce a mixture of single-seat districts and
proportional representation, to replace Japan's unique system of large
multi-seat constituencies. The new system aims to encourage politicians to
attract voters with policies, rather than cash and construction projects.
</TEXT>
