FT  12 SEP 94 / Warning on Greek economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Greece's socialist prime minister, Mr Andreas Papandreou, has warned that
the country's economy is not expected to recover before 1996. He said his
government would maintain tight austerity policies over the next 12 months.
The opening of the Thessaloniki trade fair at the weekend, Mr Papandreou
said inflation would be held at 11 per cent this year, close to the
government's target of 10.5 per cent. 'Next year's budget is being prepared
in a spirit of austerity so that borrowing needs can be further reduced, but
it will be a difficult year that will decide the economy's future course,'
he said.
Public sector wage rises are to be held at 6 per cent next year, below the
projected 8 per cent inflation rate. Growth in gross domestic product is
forecast at 1.2 per cent, against 0.8 per cent this year. Mr Papandreou's
remarks, coming a few days before Greece's economic convergence plan is
submitted for approval by European Union finance ministers, appeared
intended to reassure European Commission officials suspicious that Greece's
commitment to reducing fiscal imbalances may start to weaken.
