<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Ill-prepared Dow slumps on
PPI data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks stumbled yesterday as news of a sharp increase in producer prices
rattled the bond market, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 33.65 lower at 3,874.81, after
recovering somewhat from its worst level of the session. The Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 was down 4.96 at 468.18, reflecting the broad base of the
sell-off. Declining issues outnumbered advances on the Big Board, 1,652 to
570. Volume was moderate, with 293m shares traded by the close.
The American SE composite fared a little better, dipping 0.97 to 454.5. The
Nasdaq composite shed 4.96 to 763.76 as a two-day rally by technology stocks
sputtered out.
In spite of indications to the contrary, the market was ill prepared for the
bad news on inflation delivered by the Labor Department. Stocks across the
board went into a tail-spin as trading opened, with investors jolted by the
announcement of a 0.6 per cent increase in the August producer price index.
A 0.5 per cent gain had been forecast.
Before the session began, the strong reading set off alarm in the bond
market, where a wave of selling pushed the yield on the benchmark 30-year
Treasury to over 7.70 per cent, its highest level since mid-July.
After sliding more than 40 points in the first hour, the Dow industrials
were able to stabilise and retrace some lost ground. A second downturn came
during the afternoon, but the blue chip battled back again. Still, as the
session closed, 23 out of the index's 30 components were showing losses,
three were unchanged and a six held slender gains.
Rate-sensitive stocks were among the hardest hit, as some investors feared
higher inflation would bring forward the Federal Reserve's next tightening
of monetary policy.
In banking, Bankers Trust dropped Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 70, JP Morgan
retreated Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 63 1/2 and Wells Fargo shed Dollars 2 to
Dollars 154 5/8 . Morgan Stanley, the Wall Street securities house, lost
Dollars 2 to Dollars 65 7/8 .
In retailing, JP Penney slumped Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 52 7/8 and Gap
Stores retreated Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 36 3/4 .
An 8 per cent decline in USAir's share valuation was unrelated to the day's
economic developments. The issue was marked down Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 6
1/8 after one of the carrier's domestic flights crashed near Pittsburgh,
killing 132 passengers and crew members.
Canada
Toronto stocks plunged to close sharply lower as US inflation data rocked
North American financial markets.
The TSE-300 index fell 25.24 at 4,329.14 in volume of 66.57m shares valued
at CDollars 715.9m. Advancing stocks led declines 344 to 411 with 305 issues
unchanged.
All of Toronto's 14 sub-sectors fell, except for precious metals which
bucked the TSE trend on an improving gold price. December gold on COMEX
closed USDollars 1.20 higher at USDollars 395.80 per ounce in heavy volume.
Brazil
Sao Paulo rallied for the third session in a row to close up 1.5 per cent in
heavy trade boosted by renewed confidence in Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso's
presidential candidacy.
The Bovespa index ended up 790 at 53,511 points. Stocks rose 11.4 per cent
over the last three days, shrugging off a 10.5 per cent plunge on Monday
sparked by the resignation of Mr Rubens Ricupero, the former economy
minister.
Turnover was RDollars 362.4m (Dollars 419m). Telebras TEL. SA preferred
closed up 0.4 per cent at 51.70 reais.
</TEXT>
