<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 94 / International Company News: State calls halt to bid for BPA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Portuguese government last night vetoed a Es132bn (Dollars 832m) hostile
bid for a controlling stake of 40 per cent of Banco Portugues do Atlantico
(BPA), the country's second largest bank, by Banco Comercial Portugues
(BCP).
The finance ministry said it blocked the bid partly because control of BPA
by BCP, the fifth biggest bank, could destabilise the financial system. The
new group would have controlled 24 per cent of Portugal's banking assets.
The takeover would have also interrupted the privatisation of BPA, according
to a government statement. The bank has been privatised in stages since 1990
but the state still holds 24.5 per cent.
The core shareholders of BPA, a group of 13 Portuguese companies which own
28.7 per cent, have said the government is committed to giving them
preferential treatment in the privatation process. But BCP has urged the
government to sell its holding to the highest bidder.
The government decision is expected to draw strong criticism from financial
circles for intervening in the free operation of the market. 'The government
is seeking to hold back a trend towards the merger of banking groups that is
already widespread in the rest of Europe,' said Mr Vitor Contancio, a former
governor of the Bank of Portugal and member of the opposition Socialist
Party.
</TEXT>
