<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 94 / Government privacy proposals could slow paper inquiries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government proposals for new legal safeguards against the invasion of
privacy would deter legitimate inquiries by newspapers, a Liberal Democrat
committee warned yesterday, Ivor Owen writes.
The party's press and broadcasting working group believes that invasions of
personal privacy should continue to be dealt with case-by-case by the
courts.
It maintains in a document for the party's conference later this month that,
while a privacy law might assist some victims of press intrusion, it would
also allow others to deter legitimate inquiries with the threat of legal
action.
However, it favours carefully tailored criminal offences of physical
intrusion to deter peeping toms and aggressive 'doorstepping' by the press.
