<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / World Stock Markets: Rumours spur Sao Paulo
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil
Sao Paulo closed 5.68 per cent higher, propelled by rumours that a new
opinion poll expected later that day would show Mr Fernando Henrique
Cardoso, the ruling party candidate, maintaining his lead in the
presidential race.
The Bovespa index of the 55 most active shares added 2,834 at 52,721 and
turnover totalled RDollars 355.3m (Dollars 404.2m).
Brokers reported only slow foreign activity, saying that most deals were
concentrated in day-trade operations by domestic investors. Foreigners, they
added, were staying on the sidelines, waiting for new presidential election
developments.
Mexico
Shares continued the rally that began late on Tuesday, after the two weeks
of declines which had followed the elections on August 21. The IPC index
finished 23.24, or 0.85 per cent, up at 2,762.16. At the end of 1993 the IPC
stood at 2,602.63.
Traders said local investors warmed to the upward movement of Mexican blue
chips on Wall Street.
