<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Strength in 3M sets tone for
upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US equity investors went bargain hunting yesterday, lifting share prices
across the board after a string of soft sessions, writes Frank McGurty in
New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 22.21 ahead at 3,908.46, while the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 gained 2.18 at 473.14. On the Big Board, advances led
declines by 1,315 to 806 after volume of 296m shares.
The American SE composite edged up 0.19 to 455.51, while the Nasdaq
composite again outperformed the rest of the indices, climbing 5.02 to
769.30.
The day's second-tier economic news was virtually ignored. The focus was
still set squarely on today's report on August producer prices.
The market awaited the report with a mixture of resignation and quiet
confidence. On one hand, most investors expected to be handed clear evidence
of accelerating inflation. Analysts were forecasting an increase of about
0.5 per cent in producer prices, or about 0.3 per cent excluding the
volatile food and energy sectors.
But there was also a consensus that the data would not prompt the Federal
Reserve to bring forward its next monetary tightening, even if it came in
stronger than expected. After losing ground in four of the last five
sessions, the market appeared to have already factored some bad inflation
news into stock valuations.
As a consequence, the stage was set yesterday morning for investors to bid
up stock prices in response to a firming trend in bonds and improvement by
the dollar in the foreign exchange markets.
Later in the day, bonds wavered but the bellwether Dow industrials remained
well above the 3,900 level.
Among the blue chips, 3M set the pace with a rise of Dollars 1 3/4 to
Dollars 56 3/8 . The stock, which had receded over the past fortnight,
forged ahead after the company predicted that its earnings per share would
improve by 10 per cent annually over the next three years.
In retailing, Sears Roebuck moved forward Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 48 5/8 ,
while Kmart added Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 18 in a muted reaction to the
company's decision to close 110 stores and cut its management ranks by 10
per cent.
The rally in technology stocks - the biggest surprise of a rather
predictable week - stretched into a second session. Texas Instruments, up
Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars 77 1/8 , led the semiconductor sector, while
Compaq, Dollars 1 stronger at Dollars 36 5/8 , was to the fore in computer
makers.
On the Nasdaq, Microsoft put on Dollars 1 at Dollars 57 7/8 and Atmel rose
Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 28 3/4.
Canada
Toronto rallied as investors were heartened by the results of an opinion
poll showing the ruling Liberals ahead of the Parti Quebecois for the first
time in the Quebec election campaign. The provincial election takes place on
Monday.
The TSE 300 index ended 15.31 points firmer at 4,354.38 and rises outscored
falls by 396 to 340 after volume of 67.5m shares valued at CDollars 798.3m.
Nine of the 14 sub-indices were higher, led by mining, consumer products,
financial services and forestry products. The golds index, after recent
strength, slipped 0.52 per cent.
</TEXT>
